    Free-range Chicken Bhuna with Fragrant Peanut Rice

    Forget the takeaway: this curry is bursting with fresh flavour. Ginger, garlic and bhuna spices sizzle with tender free-range British chicken breasts. Add juicy tomatoes, peppers, onions and wilted spinach. Serve with rice, packed with nutty peanuts for extra crunch!
    Cook time: 35 mins
    Cuisine: Indian
    Food group: Poultry
    Key ingredient: British free-range diced chicken breast
    Allergens: Mustard, Peanuts
    May contain: Nuts, Sesame

    Ingredients

    • 600g diced British chicken breast
    • 1 onion
    • 2 pepper
    • 80g baby spinach
    • 40g roasted peanuts (Peanuts. May contain Nuts, Sesame)
    • 400g passata
    • 8 tsp ginger & garlic paste
    • 2 tbsp bhuna spice blend (Mustard)
    • 1 tbsp curry powder
    • 1 tsp fennel seeds
    • 200g seasonal tomatoes
    • 200g brown rice

    Nutritional Information

    Calories: 585
    Protein: 48g
    Carbs: 61g
    Fat: 17g

    Cooking Instructions

    Before you start
  • Bring a large saucepan filled with salted water to a boil Pull out a large frying pan, a measuring jug & a sieve
  • Get the rice on
    • Add the rice to the saucepan and boil for 25-30 mins, until cooked, then drain
  • Soften the veg
    • Thinly slice the onion and peppers
    • Heat the large frying pan with 1 tbsp oil on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the onion and pepper and cook for 5-7 mins, until softened. Season with salt and pepper
    • Meanwhile, halve the tomatoes. Rinse the spinach
  • Get the curry going
    • Add the ginger & garlic paste, fennel seeds, bhuna spice blend, and curry powder to the pan and cook for 1-2 mins, until fragrant
    • Add the chicken, stir well to coat it in the spices, then cook for 4 mins, until golden
    • Add the tomatoes, passata and 200ml water, bring to a boil then simmer for 13 mins, until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce thickens
    • Add the spinach in the last minute of cooking
  • Meanwhile, finish the rice
    • Wipe the saucepan clean and reheat with 1 tbsp oil on medium heat. Once hot, add the peanuts and cook for 1-2 mins, until fragrant
    • Add the cooked rice back to the saucepan and stir. Season with salt and pepper
  • Plate up
    • Check your chicken is cooked through by cutting a large piece in half; the flesh should be white and the juices running clear
    • Serve the chicken bhuna into bowls alongside the peanut rice
